<sect>Introduction
<p>pvmproject is a parrallel projection program designed to handle very large
(gigabyte) sized files.

<sect1>Changes
<p>

<sect>Installation
<p>
<sect1>How to obtain PVMProject 
<p>
PVMProject should be freely availble from the MCMC gigabyte project web page<p>

<sect1>Requirements
<p>
libtiff, libgeotiff, gctpc, USGS ImageLib, USGS Projectionlib, USGS ProjectionMesh,<p>
USGS ProjectionIO and USGS Mathlib

<sect1>Compilation and installation
<p>

In order to compile and install PVMProject on your system, install the requirements<p>
and type the following in the base directory of the PVMProject distribution:

<tscreen><verb>
% ./configure
% make
% make install
</verb></tscreen>

<p>
Since PVMProject uses <verb>autoconf</verb> you should not have any trouble
compiling it.
Should you run into problems please report them to the the author at 
<htmlurl url="mailto:cbilderback@usgs.gov" name = "">


<p>
<sect> Usage <p>
<sect1> General Usage
<p>
<tscreen><verb>
pvmproject [configfile]
</verb></tscreen><p>
configfile is configuration generated from previous projection runs.
<p>
If a configfile is not specified then the user will be prompted to
generate a configuration.

<p>
<sect>Questions and Answers<p>
Q: What is the parameter file?<p>
<tscreen>A: It is a text file that describes your desired output projection.</tscreen><p>
Q: What is PVM?<p>
<tscreen>A: See www.pvm.org.</tscreen><p>
Q: Can pvmproject be used on heterogenous clusters?<p>
<tscreen>A: Yes.  Change your pvmd host file for each machine type.</tscreen><p>

